Why Coroutines?


Before coroutines, Android used:

Callbacks → messy (“callback hell”)
Threads → hard to manage
RxJava → powerful but steep learning curve

Coroutines solve this by:

Making async code look like sync code
Managing threads automatically
Being lifecycle-aware (with ViewModel)


🔹 Key Concepts

1. Coroutine Scope

Defines lifecycle of coroutine

In Android:

viewModelScope → tied to ViewModel
lifecycleScope → tied to Activity/Fragment


viewModelScope.launch {
    // safe, auto-cancelled when ViewModel is cleared
}

2. Dispatchers (Threading)

Controls which thread coroutine runs on:

Dispatchers.Main → UI thread
Dispatchers.IO → network/database
Dispatchers.Default → CPU work
viewModelScope.launch(Dispatchers.IO) {
    val data = api.getData()
}


3. suspend Functions

Functions that can pause and resume

suspend fun fetchUser(): User {
    return api.getUser()
}

4. Structured Concurrency

Coroutines are hierarchical:

If parent is cancelled → children are cancelled
viewModelScope.launch {
    val user = async { api.getUser() }
    val transactions = async { api.getTransactions() }

    updateUI(user.await(), transactions.await())
}
5. Exception Handling
viewModelScope.launch {
    try {
        val data = repository.getData()
    } catch (e: Exception) {
        // handle error
    }



    🔹 Quick Summary
